{{Infobox summit | summit_name = NATO Summit London 1990 | other_titles = 1990 London Summit | image = | caption = | country = United Kingdom | venues = | cities = [[London]] | date = 5–6 July 1990 | website = }} The '''1990 London summit''' was the 10th [[NATO summit]] since 1949, and the 4th in 6 years.<ref name=NATO-E>{{cite web|title=NATO e-Library: Summits and ministerial meetings|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/comm.htm|website=nato.int|publisher=North Atlantic Treaty Organization|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> It was held in [[London, England|London]] on 5–6 July 1990. The principal outcome of the summit was the ''London Declaration on a Transformed North Atlantic Alliance''.<ref name=NATO-E />
The declaration, shaped in the midst of a changing Europe, called for substantial changes in the organization to ensure it could adapt to a rapidly evolving political landscape.<ref name=NATO-CMD>{{cite web|title=NATO's Command Structure: The Old and the New|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/topics_69718.htm|website=nato.int|publisher=North Atlantic Treaty Organization|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> Additionally, the declaration called for reductions in short-range nuclear capabilities, and re-focusing its long-term strategic plans with associated changes to the structure and quantity of its military.
Notably, the declaration also reinforced a message given days earlier stating that NATO no longer saw the Warsaw Pact countries as enemies,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rimanelli|first1=Marco|title=The A to Z of NATO and Other International Security Organizations|date=14 September 2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0810868991|page=94}}</ref> and opening up channels for communication and aid with the former eastern bloc states.<ref name=DOD>{{cite web|title=United States Security Strategy for Europe and Nato|url=http://www.dod.mil/pubs/europe/chapter_2.html|publisher=United States Depeartment of Defense|accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref> NATO extended a "hand of friendship" to eastern European nations.<ref name=NATO-ART>{{cite web|title=1990 Summit: a turning point in 'East-West' relations|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_116133.htm?selectedLocale=en|website=nato.int|publisher=North Atlantic Treaty Organization|accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>
One year later, on 20 December 1991, NATO and former members of the Warsaw Pact formed the North Atlantic Cooperation Council (NACC), now called the [[Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council]].
